<h2 id="install">Install</h2>
<p>
  WhatCable is signed with a Developer ID and notarised by Apple, so there are no Gatekeeper warnings. Requires macOS 14 (Sonoma) or later, Apple Silicon only.
</p>

<div class="install-grid">
  <div class="install-card">
    <h3>Direct download</h3>
    <p>
      Grab the latest <code>WhatCable.zip</code> from GitHub Releases, unzip, and drag <strong>WhatCable.app</strong> into your Applications folder.
    </p>
    <a class="button" href="{{ site.downloadUrl }}" download>Get the latest release</a>
  </div>

  <div class="install-card">
    <h3>Homebrew</h3>
    <p>
      Two commands. Also adds the <code>whatcable</code> CLI to your PATH automatically.
    </p>
<pre>brew tap darrylmorley/whatcable
brew install --cask whatcable</pre>
    <button type="button" class="button" data-copy="brew tap darrylmorley/whatcable &amp;&amp; brew install --cask whatcable" onclick="copyCommand(this)" style="margin-top: 14px;">
      Copy command
    </button>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note">
  <strong>Not on the Mac App Store on purpose.</strong> App Sandbox blocks the low-level IOKit reads WhatCable depends on, so it ships signed and notarised outside the store instead.
</div>

<h2 id="what-it-shows">What it shows</h2>
<p>
  WhatCable sits in your menu bar. Click the icon to see a popover with one card per USB-C port on your Mac.
  Each card shows, in plain English:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Headline:</strong> Thunderbolt / USB4, USB-C with video, Display connected, USB device, Slow USB device or charge-only cable, Charging, Plugged in &middot; battery full, or Nothing connected. When a charger is attached, the headline gains a <em>&middot; NW charger</em> suffix, plus <em>&middot; NW cable</em> when the cable is the bottleneck.</li>
  <li><strong>Charging diagnostic:</strong> whether the cable, charger, or Mac is the bottleneck, with the negotiated wattage.</li>
  <li><strong>Data-speed diagnostic:</strong> a plain-English verdict on what is limiting the link, the Mac port, the cable, or the device, so you know whether a faster cable would actually help.</li>
  <li><strong>Cable e-marker info:</strong> the cable's actual speed (USB 2.0 up to 80 Gbps), current rating (3A or 5A), and the e-marker chip vendor.</li>
  <li><strong>Cable identification:</strong> if the cable's e-marker fingerprint matches one in the bundled <a href="/cables">cable database</a>, the brand and model are shown alongside the raw specs.</li>
  <li><strong>Charger PDO list:</strong> every voltage profile the charger advertises (5V, 9V, 15V, 20V, etc.), with the active one highlighted.</li>
  <li><strong>Connected device:</strong> vendor name and product type from the PD Discover Identity response.</li>
  <li><strong>USB devices:</strong> storage, hubs, and peripherals listed under the port they are plugged into, with their negotiated speed.</li>
  <li><strong>Active transports:</strong> USB 2, USB 3, Thunderbolt, and DisplayPort paths.</li>
</ul>

