<h2 id="menu">Right-click menu</h2>
<p>
  Right-click (or Control-click) the menu bar icon for quick actions:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Refresh:</strong> re-scan all ports immediately.</li>
  <li><strong>Keep window open:</strong> pin the popover so it stays visible. Handy for screenshots, demos, or comparing cables side by side.</li>
  <li><strong>Settings…:</strong> open the Settings panel. Same as clicking the gear icon in the popover.</li>
  <li><strong>Power Monitor</strong> <span class="pro-badge">Pro</span>: open the standalone power monitor window with live charts.</li>
  <li><strong>Negotiation Diagnostics</strong> <span class="pro-badge">Pro</span>: open the per-port negotiation breakdown.</li>
  <li><strong>Licence…:</strong> enter or manage your Pro licence key.</li>
  <li><strong>Check for Updates:</strong> look for a newer version on GitHub.</li>
  <li><strong>Contribute Diagnostic Data…:</strong> run the bundled diagnostic test kit and submit anonymised port and power dumps to help improve hardware coverage.</li>
  <li><strong>About</strong> and <strong>WhatCable on GitHub:</strong> links to the project.</li>
  <li><strong>Quit:</strong> close the app.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="notifications">Notifications</h2>
<p>
  WhatCable can send a macOS notification whenever a USB device or charger connects or disconnects. This is off by default. Turn it on in Settings.
</p>
<p>
  When you enable it, macOS will ask for notification permission. Notifications are silent (no sound) and show the device name, speed, and vendor for connections, or a count for disconnections.
</p>
<p>
  Notifications work even when the popover is closed. WhatCable runs its own background watchers for USB and power source changes. It primes a baseline at launch so you do not get a burst of "connected" alerts for things that were already plugged in.
</p>

<h2 id="settings">Settings</h2>
<p>
  Click the gear icon in the popover header to open Settings. The panel is grouped into sections that match the in-app layout:
</p>

<h3>Behavior</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Launch at login:</strong> start WhatCable automatically when you log in.</li>
  <li><strong>Show in menu bar:</strong> by default WhatCable lives in the menu bar with no Dock icon. Turn this off to run it as a regular Dock app with a window.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Display</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Show technical details:</strong> permanently enable engineer mode (the raw IOKit property view). Same as holding Option when you click the icon, but stays on.</li>
  <li><strong>Hide empty ports:</strong> only show ports with something plugged in.</li>
  <li><strong>Font size:</strong> adjust the text size in the popover. Ranges from 80% to 140% of the default.</li>
  <li><strong>Language:</strong> override the system language. Eleven options plus System Default: Deutsch, English, Español, Français, Italiano, Norsk Bokmål [Norwegian], Polski, हिन्दी [Hindi], 日本語 [Japanese], 中文 (简体) [Simplified Chinese], and Հայերեն [Armenian]. WhatCable picks up the change on its next launch.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Notifications</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Notify on cable changes:</strong> get alerts when USB devices or chargers connect and disconnect.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Community</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Contribute Diagnostic Data:</strong> opt-in submission of anonymised port and power dumps. Helps build out hardware coverage across the Mac lineup. Off until you start a run yourself.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Pro</h3>
<ul>
