<h2 id="contribute">Contribute Diagnostic Data</h2>
<p>
  WhatCable can submit anonymised diagnostic data to help expand hardware coverage. It is opt-in: nothing happens in the background, and a run only starts when you explicitly approve it.
</p>
<p>
  Three entry points start a run, all leading to the same consent screen:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Right-click the menu bar icon and choose <strong>Contribute Diagnostic Data…</strong></li>
  <li>Open <strong>Settings</strong> and use the <strong>Community</strong> section</li>
  <li>From a terminal: <code>whatcable --test-kit</code> (with a y/N confirmation)</li>
</ul>

<h3>What is sent</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Raw IOKit registry data from 13 small one-shot probes, covering port state, USB-PD identity, Thunderbolt link details, and HPM telemetry.</li>
  <li>Your macOS version and chip family (for example, Apple M3 Pro).</li>
  <li>A SHA-256 hash of your Mac's UUID, used to stitch the 13 probes together without storing the underlying ID.</li>
</ul>

<h3>What is not sent</h3>
<ul>
  <li>No names, email addresses, serial numbers, or personal data.</li>
  <li>No analytics or background telemetry. The only network call WhatCable makes on its own is the six-hourly update check.</li>
  <li>Re-running from the same Mac overwrites your previous submission rather than adding to it, so we do not accumulate a timeline.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="pro">Pro features</h2>
<p>
  <a href="/pro">WhatCable Pro</a> is a one-time purchase that adds deeper diagnostics on top of everything in the free app. All free features stay free. Pro adds the following:
</p>

<h3>Negotiation Diagnostics <span class="pro-badge">Pro</span></h3>
<p>
  The free app gives a one-line verdict on what is limiting a connection. Pro shows the full breakdown: what the Mac port, the cable, and the device each support, side by side with what was actually negotiated and the weak link highlighted, plus a cross-check of the cable's e-marker against the Thunderbolt controller so a cable that under-reports itself is caught. Pro screens open inside the app, with an optional detach into their own window so a screen can stay open while you swap cables.
</p>

